# 24f7a7988f28425dbf875821ede187fa
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:23
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

# e58a00ac170a4086bdd0f6aea21a3133
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:25
msgid ""
"Global data networking has become part of everyday life: Internet users "
"request billions of documents and petabytes of data, on a daily basis, to"
" and from all parts of the world. Information is free, abundant, and "
"accessible. Unfortunately, global data networking can also be a nightmare"
" for IT professionals as they struggle with overloaded servers and "
"congested networks. It can be challenging to consistently and reliably "
"accommodate society’s growing data demands."
msgstr ""

# d77071c0d75a43ef92a07febb7fdedb4
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:33
msgid ""
"Traffic Server is a high-performance web proxy cache that improves "
"network efficiency and performance by caching frequently-accessed "
"information at the edge of the network. This brings content physically "
"closer to end users, while enabling faster delivery and reduced bandwidth"
" use. Traffic Server is designed to improve content delivery for "
"enterprises, Internet service providers (ISPs), backbone providers, and "
"large intranets by maximizing existing and available bandwidth."
msgstr ""

# bfea4a0191434cfcb61d9ef21bef5ced
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:42
msgid "Traffic Server Deployment Options"
msgstr ""

# 599c34b714644076a928eb53f655681b
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:44
msgid "To best suit your needs, Traffic Server can be deployed in several ways:"
msgstr ""

# 4145d463195742d8bb2d171da0d90e2a
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:46
msgid "As a web proxy cache"
msgstr ""

# f8fd8580524742d68fcb791f57d6fcd1
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:47
msgid "As a reverse proxy"
msgstr ""

# 76aad53b68cd4356b75ea7324b417ecc
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:48
msgid "In a cache hierarchy"
msgstr ""

# 691b5e21ec8b4b2fa362adc829dc7af2
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:50
msgid ""
"The following sections provide a summary of these Traffic Server "
"deployment options. Please keep in mind that with every one of these "
"options Traffic Server can be run as a *single instance*, or as a *multi-"
"node cluster*."
msgstr ""

# d75614d5e94e46d885787a64f909b772
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:55
msgid "Traffic Server as a Web Proxy Cache"
msgstr ""

# 39612c9854ee45f3ae3621ea0ac96221
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:57
msgid ""
"As a web proxy cache, Traffic Server receives user requests for web "
"content as those requests travel to the destined web server (origin "
"server). If Traffic Server contains the requested content, then it serves"
" the content directly. If the requested content is not available from "
"cache, then Traffic Server acts as a proxy: it obtains the content from "
"the origin server on the user’s behalf and also keeps a copy to satisfy "
"future requests."
msgstr ""

# 08e77282fe324e7f8f2cb846b7882c93
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:65
msgid ""
"Traffic Server provides explicit proxy caching, in which the user’s "
"client software must be configured to send requests directly to Traffic "
"Server. Explicit proxy caching is described in the :ref:`explicit-proxy-"
"caching` chapter."
msgstr ""

# 7471797c5c4840c6853132fa170fe919
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:70
msgid ""
"Traffic Server can also be employed as a transparent caching proxy "
"server, in which the client software needs no special configuration or "
"even knowledge of the proxy's existence. This setup is described in the "
":ref:`transparent-proxy` section."
msgstr ""

# 495d2c86cc9c495998e363d201c0d2de
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:76
msgid "Traffic Server as a Reverse Proxy"
msgstr ""

# 93f4204c8d7842b9970ef331f0713fcb
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:78
msgid ""
"As a reverse proxy, Traffic Server is configured to be the origin server "
"to which the user is trying to connect (typically, the origin server’s "
"advertised hostname resolves to Traffic Server, which acts as the real "
"origin server). The reverse proxy feature is also called server "
"acceleration. Reverse proxy is described in more detail in :ref:`reverse-"
"proxy-and-http-redirects`."
msgstr ""

# 08ed7b937fb944fcb975af9dc3cc9ea2
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:86
msgid "Traffic Server in a Cache Hierarchy"
msgstr ""

# 4316d2490de247c0a7ac3ee3d286e206
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:88
msgid ""
"Traffic Server can participate in flexible cache hierarchies, in which "
"Internet requests not fulfilled from one cache are routed to other "
"regional caches, thereby leveraging the contents and proximity of nearby "
"caches. In a hierarchy of proxy servers, Traffic Server can act either as"
" a parent or a child cache to other Traffic Server systems or to similar "
"caching products."
msgstr ""

# 8c6d8458e36541e1b5c4a7d016345c38
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:95
msgid ""
"Traffic Server supports ICP (Internet Cache Protocol) peering. "
"Hierarchical caching is described in more detail in :ref:`admin-"
"hierarchical-caching`."
msgstr ""

# beb9a426e849439096c621c783b230df
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:99
msgid "Deployment Limitations"
msgstr ""

# 022d1762f8514dc496cd7cc80fc58aa0
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:101
msgid ""
"There are a number of deployment options that Traffic Server does not "
"support right out of the box. Such functionality may be implemented in a "
"plugin, but in some cases Traffic Server's internal APIs or architectural"
" restrictions won't make it easy:"
msgstr ""

# ee1d674e602e4d2c9a0ae251a7b28072
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:106
msgid ""
"Load Balancing - note that there is an experimental plugin for this: :ref"
":`balancer-plugin`."
msgstr ""

# 59badfe0ba76417886f7d76ecef83ffd
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:111
msgid "Traffic Server Components"
msgstr ""

# c111332c643f49929779bc4d83481c0c
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:113
msgid ""
"Traffic Server consists of several components that work together to form "
"a web proxy cache you can easily monitor and configure."
msgstr ""

# c2bb67e74a6a44e98b88e56c0bbff920
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:117
msgid "The Traffic Server Cache"
msgstr ""

# 5a7e61d0528a43fabd01149ce54ba161
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:119
msgid ""
"The Traffic Server cache consists of a high-speed object database called "
"the *object store*. The object store indexes objects according to URLs "
"and associated headers. Using sophisticated object management, the object"
" store can cache alternate versions of the same object (perhaps in a "
"different language or encoding type). It can also efficiently store very "
"small and very large objects, thereby minimizing wasted space. When the "
"cache is full, Traffic Server removes stale data to ensure that the most "
"requested objects are readily available and fresh."
msgstr ""

# c1b7282472de4512b140111bf8f0c369
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:128
msgid ""
"Traffic Server is designed to tolerate total disk failures on any of the "
"cache disks. If the disk fails completely, then Traffic Server marks the "
"entire disk as corrupt and continues to use remaining disks. If all of "
"the cache disks fail, then Traffic Server switches to proxy-only mode. "
"You can partition the cache to reserve a certain amount of disk space for"
" storing data for specific protocols and origin servers. For more "
"information about the cache, see :ref:`http-proxy-caching`."
msgstr ""

# be3f15b013164cd6b20a22c4d6cf52e6
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:137
msgid "The RAM Cache"
msgstr ""

# b0b9fed0554a494eae1222593f86711d
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:139
msgid ""
"Traffic Server maintains a small RAM cache that contains extremely "
"popular objects. This RAM cache serves the most popular objects as fast "
"as possible and reduces load on disks, especially during temporary "
"traffic peaks. You can configure the RAM cache size to suit your needs. "
"For detailed information, refer to :ref:`changing-the-size-of-the-ram-"
"cache`."
msgstr ""

# e72cc517202d4be0adeae9d3453dd2fb
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:146
msgid "The Host Database"
msgstr ""

# 73bb1041eb7741cb84d39e2171124aec
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:148
msgid ""
"The Traffic Server host database stores the domain name server (DNS) "
"entries of origin servers to which Traffic Server connects to fulfill "
"user requests. This information is used to adapt future protocol "
"interactions and optimize performance. Along with other information, the "
"host database tracks:"
msgstr ""

# ea5c921e43c443de9a37c8e869d7c0c2
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:154
msgid "DNS information (for fast conversion of hostnames to IP addresses)."
msgstr ""

# f2474a5dce4742cbafb9faa2f458afe2
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:156
msgid ""
"The HTTP version of each host (so advanced protocol features can be used "
"with hosts running modern servers)."
msgstr ""

# dbb6c880de5b4cafba720efa95653b72
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:159
msgid ""
"Host reliability and availability information (so users will not wait for"
" servers that are not running)."
msgstr ""

# 49b9dee034df4f8e9a5d412f87d01b9d
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:163
msgid "The DNS Resolver"
msgstr ""

# fb1314f4c49c474a8999a02adeb3ab5b
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:165
msgid ""
"Traffic Server includes a fast, asynchronous DNS resolver to streamline "
"conversion of hostnames to IP addresses. Traffic Server implements the "
"DNS resolver natively by directly issuing DNS command packets rather than"
" relying on slower, conventional resolver libraries. Since many DNS "
"queries can be issued in parallel and a fast DNS cache maintains popular "
"bindings in memory, DNS traffic is reduced."
msgstr ""

# d5dc846a6c054af9bc80c1ccaf0795af
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:173
msgid "Traffic Server Processes"
msgstr ""

# 5ce64be325de4d7a92e55f2f52b67f63
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:175
msgid ""
"Traffic Server contains three processes that work together to serve "
"requests and manage, control, and monitor the health of the system."
msgstr ""

# 0d0e94abec2a4bff9fdf7ac82aa782ce
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:178
msgid ""
"The :program:`traffic_server` process is the transaction processing "
"engine of Traffic Server. It is responsible for accepting connections, "
"processing protocol requests, and serving documents from the cache or "
"origin server."
msgstr ""

# 27f234b2c4e14c52aa8047185b3d4c2c
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:183
msgid ""
"The :program:`traffic_manager` process is the command and control "
"facility of the Traffic Server, responsible for launching, monitoring, "
"and reconfiguring the :program:`traffic_server` process. The "
":program:`traffic_manager` process is also responsible for the proxy "
"autoconfiguration port, the statistics interface, cluster administration,"
" and virtual IP failover."
msgstr ""

# 5d25d6d889ff4a77ab0b183f6fa70a02
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:190
msgid ""
"If the :program:`traffic_manager` process detects a "
":program:`traffic_server` process failure, it instantly restarts the "
"process but also maintains a connection queue of all incoming requests. "
"All incoming connections that arrive in the several seconds before full "
"server restart are saved in the connection queue and processed in first-"
"come, first-served order. This connection queueing shields users from any"
" server restart downtime."
msgstr ""

# 9ab7a87b43594659a5f59684e516582a
#: ../../admin-guide/introduction.en.rst:198
msgid ""
"The :program:`traffic_cop` process monitors the health of both the "
":program:`traffic_server` and :program:`traffic_manager` processes. The "
":program:`traffic_cop` process periodically (several times each minute) "
"queries the :program:`traffic_server` and :program:`traffic_manager` "
"processes by issuing heartbeat requests to fetch synthetic web pages. In "
"the event of failure (if no response is received within a timeout "
"interval or if an incorrect response is received), :program:`traffic_cop`"
" restarts the :program:`traffic_manager` and :program:`traffic_server` "
"processes."
msgstr ""

